<DOC><DOCNO> AP891020-0139 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1340EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-PentagonProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0609 10-20 0367</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Pentagon Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,340</SECOND><HEAD>Former Sperry Official Admits Role in Bribery Scheme</HEAD><HEAD>EDS: SUBS pvs 3rd graf, Lavelle, a, to CORRECT maximum fines to $30,000sted $500,000</HEAD><BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former Sperry Corp. marketing executivepleaded guilty today to charges he participated in a scheme tobribe a Navy official as part of an effort to get a lucrativeelectronics contract.   Frank J. Lavelle, 68, pleaded guilty to conspiracy and briberyin connection with payment of $400,000 to Garland L. Tomlin, Jr., aformer Navy procurement official.   Lavelle, a former marketing director for Sperry's Clearwater,Fla., facility, faces a possible 20-year prison sentence and finesof $30,000 for his involvement in the bribery scheme that includedanother Sperry official and a defense consultant for the company.   Tomlin, 59, has already pleaded guilty to charges he took$400,000 from Sperry and $75,000 from Honeywell Inc. to provideconfidential bid information on a multimillion-dollar contract formaintaining electronic components of Navy weapons.   Lavelle admitted that he introduced Tomlin to Charles F.Gardner, a former Sperry executive on Long Island, N.Y., who hasalso pleaded guilty to charges arising from his role in thePentagon procurement scandal.   Lavelle told Gardner that Tomlin wanted a ``nest egg'' for hisretirement. Gardner obtained permission from another official ofSperry to approve the payments.   The money was funneled to an offshore account that Tomlin keptin the Bahamas by James G. Neal, a consultant who worked forSperry, which became part of the Unisys Corp. following a mergerwith Burroughs Corp.   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton scheduled Lavelle's sentencingfor Jan. 12, 1990.   Former Unisys marketing executive Dennis Mitchell, 42, meanwhilereceived a 90-day sentence in a halfway house for his guilty pleato participate in a scheme to pay $4,000 in illegal campaigncontributions to several members of Congress.   Mitchell was also placed on two years' probation and ordered toperform 100 hours of community service.   The contributions were funneled through Unisys consultants atthe direction of Gardner to various House members involved indefense appropriations. They included Congressmen Les Aspin, theWisconsin Democrat who chairs the House Armed Services Committee.</TEXT></DOC>